description.text: I never use my right extruder, so to extend the life of my gantry motors, I removed it (along with the motor) and replaced the whole motor-extruder assembly with these two parts. The fan duct can be installed from the top (recycle the right motor's fan and connect its leads to that of the left motor's fans) and both pillar and duct can be secured by two screws (I used a pair of 60mm M3 hex screws with nuts and lock-washers). The nozzle points a solid beam of air straight at the left extruder's tip. The result is filament that never goo's up on you due to slow hardening while printing. The image above is from my monitoring camera and you can see that the base layer that it is putting down is satiny and glassy (as opposed to grainy and stringy). You will need to install the pillar piece as it not only tidies the cables, but also serves the purpose of engaging the right home sensor. I deliberately made it point off to the side so that the electrical cables never touch the filament (which is fed from the top on mine through a 2mm hole in the top cover). Also, I do not use a filament sleeve/tube. I honestly see no point - it makes swapping filaments easy if they're just exposed. Give it a try! If you found this useful, please share your work and be sure to peruse my other submissions which are almost as varied as they are many: http://www.thingiverse.com/3E8/designs Enjoy!

comments.text: I think this is a bad idea and bad usage case. In the Firmware, left is secondary and right is primary extruder. Anytime left is used, the actuall coordinate is added in the firmware to with the toolhead offset. While a minor and small detail, this makes alignment and troubleshooting a pain. Also, you cannot switch to single extruder mode in onboard preferences as that disables the left and only uses the right primary extruder. You also technically are not getting the maximum build space possible using the left extruder if you installed a larger bed. This is because the left extruder is already left when parked at the X endstop. If you use ONLY the right extruder, switch to single mode, you can GAIN build area.

description.text:
These are some upgrade parts to improve the Folgertech 2020 printer:

  • A support for a discount controller board. I use the "Delta Panel" by Scott Mason to hold the display. (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:30330) This lifts it up above the top cross bar to keep it out of the way of the X-axis arm. I also created some brackets to "lock" the holder to the 2020 beam. They make the display a little more rigid.

  • An end cap to cover the raw 2020 aluminum ends. It snaps on.

  • A cable clip that snaps on top of the print head to keep the extruder cables neat.

  • A filament spool holder. It's designed for Hatchbox spools, but works with others. Hatchbox is using a different sized spool recently, so there's a new holder for the larger hole spools.

  • Heatsink spacers. These fit on the screws between the fan and the heatsink on the extruder to keep the fan from jutting out at an angle.

  • Cooling Fan Holder lets you mount a 40mm cooling fan pointed at the stepper motor drivers to keep them cool. Overheating stepper motor drivers can lead to a larger number of print problems. The holder just clips to the plexiglass piece that the power supply and Ramps board are mounted on. You can run the power for the fan right to the power supply.

This is a simple compact button cell battery holder for lighting a LED. The batteries I used are Duracell 303/357, also says SR44/SR44W/EPX76.
I needed it to light a rocket that I printed, where the space to fit a battery did not fit a CR232, or AA batteries. Possibly AAA batteries could have fit, but they would have blocked much of the light in the small space inside the rocket. The rocket that I made is this ornament rocket (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:39238); however, I did enlarge it to be 5.5" tall.

Insert the leads of a standard LED into the larger circle at one end, with one lead above and below the centerline, while keeping track of where the positive and negative leads are.  Connect one lead around to the opposite end, through a switch, and the other to the closest point where the batteries go. Solder in your connections well and use heat shrink tubing to cover exposed wires.  Then insert the batteries in the proper direction and try out your light switch.
I used Fusion 360 to design this button cell battery holder so it would fit inside the rocket that I printed.

description.text:
I have a number of Toy Biz Lord of the Rings action figures from 2005/2006 for which I found it difficult to find display bases that fit.  So I decided to make my own and make it customizable.
The default base is designed for a 2" diameter, 2mm height with a 3 mm peg at 4mm high.  This peg would be too large for most smaller 6" action figures.  You would need to measure the hole in the figure's foot to customize properly.  A 2mm diameter peg at 2mm height may be a good starting point for smaller figures.
This supports the following shapes:  Round, Triangle, Square, Pentagon, Hexagon, Heptagon, Octagon, Decagon and Dodecagon
TIP:  It's a good idea to print 2 or more at a time.  This gives each layer time to cool when printing the peg.  Printing a single base at a time can result in the peg warping when the next layer is printed.
NOTE:  You may need to experiment with the positioning of the peg for some shapes more than others.  The peg does not automatically adjust its position based on size or shape.  If you change the size of the base, you will need to adjust the offsets of the peg.

I tried to print the "z endstop adjuster.stl" however it always came out horribly. Attributing this to the fact that it's tiny with 2 M3 holes and nut traps I instead made my own with an integrated flag. This removes an M3 bolt & nut and takes only a little longer to print.

• 1 off 3D printed "Cantilever Z Flag.stl"
  • 3 off M3x20mm bolts
  • 3 off M3 nut
  • 2 off 5mm M3 standoffs
  • ~70mm of black electrical insulation tape

• Slice and print "Cantilever Z Flag.stl".
  • Insert the M3 nut in the nut trap making sure that it is fully seated inside so that the M3 thread lines up with the 2 holes.
  • Check that the flag triggers the opto-endstops.
    a. You may need to apply some tape in order to block the IR light from the endstops. Black electrical insulating tape works well.
  • If you've alread assembled your cantilevered Z stage you will need to remove it and remove the top plate. Then remove the current z flag assembly.
  • Fit the new z flag in place making sure to line the 3mm holes all line up.
  • Replace the top plate and then the cantilevered Z stage in your Cupcake.
  • You may need to use the white 5mm stand offs that came with your Makerbot Cupcake to correctly align the z flag and the z axis opto endstop.
    a. You will need M3x20mm bolts to do this.
  • Check your printer then turn on and print test cubes until you've calibrated your Z axis.

SolidWorks I first scavenged for parts that I had laying around in my miscellaneous parts box. I was limited to four 608ZZ bearings (the ones you find in skateboard wheels) and one 12-inch non-threaded quarter inch rod. I took the measurements of these two parts and designed around these parameters. I used Solidworks to model the designs and then exported the design as an .STL file. The slicer engine I used was Cura, which is a free, open-source slicer engine. From the slicer engine, I exported the toolpath that my 3D printer can use as an .gcode file.

Project Description Objectives: The objective of this project is to teach students and people alike what the procedure is for engineering your daily problems. This project teaches you step by step by showing you the parameters and limitations that engineers have to work around, designing,
implementing, and sharing. Audiences: The appropriate audience is anyone with a keen interest in learning, really. Preparation: Obtain the required resources, which are four 608ZZ bearings, one twelve inch, quarter inch rod (threaded or un-threaded), a 3D printer, and filament of your choice. Steps:

  • Set out to solve a problem. In our case it is, "How do you stabilize a camera for smooth recording using easy to find resources, gravity, and friction?"

  • Find your resources! i.e. scavenge or buy four 608ZZ bearings (these are bearings found in skateboard wheels) and a twelve inch, quarter inch rod (threaded or un-threaded)

  • Take the dimensions of such resources!

  • Draw sketches on paper.

  • CAD the sketches based on your sketches using your CAD software of your choice (I used Solidworks).

  • Save CAD model as .STL, export it to your slicer engine of your choice (I used Cura as it is open-source) and slice the CAD model using your preferred settings. I used .2mm walls at 15% infill)

  • Save gcode and send it to your 3D printer (I used a 3D printer kit called the RepRap Prusa i3)

  • Done!
    • Results: At the end of the project, you should have learned the procedure of engineering real engineering problem (in our case it was, "how do you stabilize a camera for smooth recording using gravity?") In doing this project, you have learned to work with limitations i.e. lack of resources prompt engineers to find cost saving solutions to reduce cost of materials by using ingenious solutions such as holding parts together via friction instead of nuts, bolts, rivets, and the like.

description.text:
This is my interactive LED table based on Arduino Mega. LED display was constructed from pegboard, white glass plate, aluminium profiles and 100 pieces of RGB WS2812B addressable leds.

  • Rainbow animation
  • Animations from Fastled library
  • Stars animation
  • VU Meter
  • DIce for games
  • Tetris game
  • Snake game

description.text: There you have a simple and flat snowflake, easy to print and assembled with cyanoacrilate, with our official Logo. A simple way to say to all: have a good 3D printed winter! All the best from ITALY!

comments.text:
Hello Elmo, you recognized the same starting geometry, it's true.
But I completely redesigned my snowflake in a vector program, and if you look carefully I didn't use the same mounting way so the shapes are different (all different).

Print Speed: 30mm/s NOTE
The success of building this puzzle depends on the accuracy of your printer. Some parts maybe be a tight fit if your printers is not calibrated well. I've scaled the gaps up a tiny bit to compensate for that.

Idea I modeled this according to a wooden puzzle I have at home. I enjoy building little puzzles like this so I thought I'd make a 3D model and print one. Design I used a free/open-sourced 3D modelling program developed by a community of software developers. It's called HeeksCNC. It's a great free program with alot a great features. It can also be used for CNC mills/routers and creating Gcode files. I, however, only used to for the 3D modelling side and saved it as an STL file.

Objectives Students can learn to think outside the box. Using common sense together with logical think, this puzzle will co-ordinate brainpower along with physical manipulation of the pieces in-order to achieve the end result. Audiences Ages 10 and up should be able to attempt this puzzle, however they might need some guides. This would really suit teenagers or highschool kids. NOTE
Look in the "Summary" section for a video if you require the solution to complete the puzzle. Preparation All that is needed to complete this puzzle is some logical thinking together with a good attitude. See the picture below for the complete set of printed parts. Steps I have provided a video (not made by me) showing the solution to this puzzle. I would definitely recommend trying it first before watching the video :D https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8rclzr24nS4 Results Students should have completed a "cross-shaped 3D cube" once complete.
